On 01 Apr 2000 23:29:03 -0600, Eric Renfro wrote:
> 
> Alex Wallis wrote (re: http://myrddincon.dynup.net/projects/fvwm-themer/):
> > 
> > Mikhael Goikhman And Olivier Chapuis, two developers from this list,
> > have been writing a perl-script based theme tool called
> > fvwm-themes-config which can be downloaded from
> > https://sourceforge.net/project/?group_id=1738
> 
> Ahh, yes, Very good resource. Yes. I tried it out, but I find only one fatal
> flaw. It requires fwvm 2.3.x, One of my big things I'm trying to do with
> fvwm-themer, is keep it supporting at least fvwm 2.0  and up.

Does this mean you will not support all nice features of fvwm-2.4?
Supporting old versions is nice, but, as it were already said, they are not
designed for themes. 2.4 will be much better and 3.0 will be better yet. :)

I think it is ok to have a separate package for each major fvwm version,
i.e. I suggest you not to port your fvwm-themer to be 2.4 compilant, but
support the mentioned fvwm-themes instead, especially if you like it.

> > It appears likely that this new themes package is going to be featured
> > on the soon to be recreated fvwm.themes.org page. However more people
> > are needed to help with bug-testing and adding additional features to
> > this project. All input is being welcomed. Currently a recent snapshot
> > of fvwm or the cvs sources are required.
> 
> That's left to be seen, so far. fvwm.t.o is going to be looking for the "most
> popular" easy to use theme engine. I know. I've already contacted them about
> it. ;)

I originally was all for it. Seems good for me to have several (not many)
competing theme formats, and my suggestion was to link to all existing
ones (and a user will choose). But others on the fvwm-themes-devel list
argued that it will be very confusing to the average fvwm.themes.org user.
Now when I see at least 10 different setups, I think, I agree.

My biggest concern about other theme setups is that they are not designed
well in my opinion. I am pretty sure that the standard fvwm-themes format
should be developed by ones who know all fvwm internals. Otherwise it will
just become another unofficial fvwm2rc format.

> > I myself have an fvwm themes configuration suite of forms available at
> > http://www.dove.net.au/~awol/fvwm2/ (bug-ridden pre-alpha only) which I
> > have just begun reworking to hopefully integrate into a full-featured
> > user-friendly interface to fvwm-themes-config. (It's only 81K)
> 
> Yes. I looked at that, too. VERY nice looking so far. I planned to do
> the same thing, using FvwmForm and/or FvwmGtk, with my new engine I'm
> working to add version checking support, I'll add a line to check for
> Gtk, and if 2.3.x+ and GTK exist, I'll have it use FvwmGtk instead.

Eric, I invite you and all others who have time to contribute to work
together and create the best fvwm-themes framework. Noone will like to
have several half functional and incompatible ones. :)

Regards,
Mikhael.
