For modules (and currently only for them) $FVWM_USERHOME is always set
and defaults, like in Read, to $HOME.

If we are speaking about this, here is an explanation why defining
  env FVWM_USERHOME=$HOME/.fvwm fvwm2 ...

as the WM command of a session menager is not enough. fvwm is restarted
by SM, and in the new process $FVWM_USERHOME is not set. So for "env ..."
to have effect, it should be added before gnome-session or xsm instead.

> I think that if the user do not set FVWM_USERHOME then
> fvwm have to set it.

I was among ones arguing setting any global environment in all spawned
processes. Now I think it is ok to have $FVWM_USERHOME to be explicitly
set if needed, for consistency, because now scripts may do the work of
modules (like fvwm-menu-* scripts). But this is not really a problem.
The problem is the $HOME default.

> Moreover, I think that the better
> idea is to set it to ~/.fvwm in this case. Why ? because
> imagine a user which start fvwm2 without config, then
> he use the Setup Form and the Form copy 10 (non cached) 
> files: DefaultFvwmBacker, Default* ... in ~/  !? 

I will post a patch doing this correctly (i.e. without breaking anything).
I had this in my queue of things to do, from the time we decided on
~/.fvwm default (before feature freeze).

