> Eric, I didn't get any answer from you. Instead, I see, you dropped support
> for 2.2 and started your new fvwm-themer for 2.4 despite of your own words
> and my suggestion to join fvwm-themes. Can you please hint us what stopped
> you from joining the existing and working project with all infrastructure?
> Do we have any flaws in design, which you like to fix?

I dropped support for 2.2 for the time being, till I can get some decent
version depenancy checking working by use of forms or FvwmScript. I figured for
the time being, with the new engine as more featured as it is, I could just
remove the 2.2 support for now, and make the current stuff work, then backtrack
it, and get 2.2.x stuff working. 
My problem with fvwm-themes is the restarting of fvwm when you make a
configuration change, the seperate options you can use amongs all the themes.
That's a bad concept, and why I went away from AfterStep, for one. Another, is,
if someone else, NOT part of the fvwm-themes team makes a theme and uses
totally different options not nicely congruently working together, you have
what I call, conflict of interest. fvwm-themer is a project I've wanted to do
for a long time, and over the period of 2 weeks, I've been doing it. Quite
successfully, so far, too. ;)
I'm not on some ego trip like a small handful might think, I just have specific
wants.

> I would simply ignore this if you would play it nice. It is ok to steal
> design parts from fvwm-themes, but it is not nice to present the project
> as "revolutional" and your own without getting any links and credits to
> the authors of fvwm-themes, from where you copy structure and ideas.

What? Steal design parts? The only thing I've even _started_ to use was the
ScriptsUtilsMessage, and I don't even have it implemented in 0.3's release. The
only other snippet I've used is now a very highly hacked up voidme theme
listing engine, as part of the initTheme section. 

> We are activelly working on fvwm-themes for more than 3 months and it is
> very extendable, so adding your new components "xrdb" and similar would be
> an easy task. It will take you a lot of time to get all the functionality
> of fvwm-themes, unless you simply copy everything from it. At least, in
> this case your setup will be compatible with the official one. :-)
> 
> I would like to get some answers from you on the questions in this message,
> and I really hope we will work together at the end doing a favor for fvwm.

I've taken 2 weeks, doing fvwm-themer, and IMHO, is right next door to your
fvwm-themes. Still have a couple design flaws, which have been temporarily
disabled for a stable release, so I could take a break for a day or two.  With
something much more ready to be released than 0.2. ;)

Eric Renfro
