Well, (2) and (3) are a matter of personal taste.  I don't like
thick lines like the 3d relief (I wouldn't bother if the line
was only one pixel) or bold fonts.  Of course this depends on
your display resolution too.  Perhaps the script should explicitly
set the relief width so that the user can easily change it (don't
ask me which setting).

> > 4) We need an 'icon box' for windows (a 'window box' :-) ).
> >    This way these icons could easily be lined up without
> >    specifying a geometry.
> 
> The icon box code probably could be generalized to place classes of windows.
> 
> One could have  a Piperead driven shell  script that would read a list
> of apps/icons to create launchers from and do  the arithmetic to place
> them.
>
> I   don't  know how  much   we should encourage    this, icons are for
> minimized applications after all.

I can think of a few situations where this would come in handy.
E.g. sometimes I have to start a number of similar shells on different
machines (e.g. windows just doing a ping).  Usually I have to spend
several minutes until all these windows are lined up nicely so that
I can see all their contents.

Well, perhaps this doesn't justify a 'window box' style.  In the end
this is only about initial placement.  You won't want the windows
rearranged when you switch pages.

Bye

Dominik ^_^

