Dominik Vogt wrote:
> 
> On Tue, Apr 11, 2000 at 06:18:15PM +0200, Dominik Vogt wrote:
> > Finally I have pinned down the rxvt selection problem to
> > a single commit.
> >
> > [The problem is that if you drag a window (you have to do it
> > fast over a rxvt window, some text in the rxvt is often
> > selected - depending on the load of the X server.  Try to
> > run 'while;true; do ls; done' in a shell on the screen to
> > keep the X server busy if necessary.]
> >
> > The problem is not present in the code I get with
> >
> >   cvs checkout -D 10/29/1999 -P -d fvwm
> >
> > and starts with
> >
> >   cvs checkout -D 10/31/1999 -P -d fvwm
> >
> > The difference in the ChangeLog is the BUSY_CURSOR patch:
> >
> >   1999-10-30  Olivier Chapuis  olivier.chapuis@free.fr
> >
> >           * NEWS: BusyCursor, EscapeFunc and CursorStyle.
> >           * fvwm/ConfigFvwmDefaults: add the binding Key Escape A MC EscapeFunc
> >           ...
> >
> >   1999-10-25  Hippo
> >
> > Olivier, can you please help debugging this?  I'm fairly sure
> > that it has something to do with 'grabbing', but I have no idea
> > what exactly could cause it.  The configure option disabling the
> > BUSYCURSOR patch doesn't fix the problem, so probably you missed
> > something with that option.  Possibly it would even happen with
> > 2.3.16 if the BUSYCURSOR patch was completely removed.  So it is
> > probably best to take the cvs from 31st or October, and remove
> > the diffs to cvs from 29th of October until the problem goes away.
> > Then we can see if the same changes to current cvs fix the problem
> > too.
> 
> Finally, the problem is solved.  It was indeed introduced by the
> BUSYCURSOR patch.  In execute_complex_function() (functions.c),
> A UngrabEm() call was moved to a delicate place:
> 
> This code around line 1439 (current CVS)
>   while(fi != NULL)
>     {
>       /* make lower case */
>       c = fi->condition;
>       ...
>         ExecuteFunction(taction,tmp_win,ev,context,-2,expand_cmd);
>       ...
>     }
>   WaitForButtonsUp(False);
>   UngrabEm();                 <-----
> 
> was changed to this:
> 
>   UngrabEm(GRAB_NORMAL);      <-----
>   while(fi != NULL)
>     {
>       /* make lower case */
>       c = fi->condition;
>       ...
>         ExecuteFunction(taction,tmp_win,ev,context,-2,expand_cmd);
>       ...
>     }
>   WaitForButtonsUp(False);
> 
> I.e. before the BUSYCURSOR patch, the pointer was grabbed throughout
> a complex function until the button was release.  After the patch
> the pointer was not grabbed anymore.  Now this explains nicely why
> the selection problem happened:
>
>  1) Press button on window title.
>  2) The pointer is grabbed automatically in the selected window.
>  3) The complex function is executed.
>  4) Before the 'Move' command is called, above code releases the
>     automatic grab on the pointer!
>  5) Move the pointer fast over another window.  Sometimes when the
>     X server is too busy, the mouse is ahead of the window.
>  6) Now, the crucial point is that the pointer is not grabbed
>     anymore.  Thus, 'MotionNotify' events are reported to the rxvt
>     because rxvt has selected them spcifically.
>  7) rxvt interprets the MotionNotify events with a button held as
>     user input and selects text in its window until the moving
>     window catches up with the pointer!!!
> 
> So, the fix is to move the UngrabEm() call back down after
> WaitForButtonsUp().  The big question is: why was it moved up
> in the first place?
 
I think that when I do the  BUSYCURSOR ifdef commit I send to you, Dominik,
a private message to say that I've do this UngrabEm() move in complex
functions when I do the busy cursor patch. At this time we conclude 
that this move was a good move. I do not remember why we do such
conclusion. I'm far from the machine I used to send to you this
message, but you may take a look to your mail archive and this
may answer the question. 
 
> Probably because you can't grab the BUSYCURSOR
> if the pointer is already grabbed. Well, Olivier, you have to
> think of a different way to achieve this.  The pointer must not
> be ungrabbed for a single CPU cycle or otherwise the problem might
> come back again.

I need to check again, but I think that your commit is consistent
with the busy cursor patch.
Olivier
