Hi, I noticed that my compiler throws the following errors on make
(gcc as included in FreeBSD 4.0-STABLE):

FvwmCpp.o: In function `cpp_defs':
/home/mikehan/fvwm/modules/FvwmCpp/FvwmCpp.c(.text+0x4d2): warning:
mktemp() possibly used unsafely; consider using mkstemp()
FvwmM4.o: In function `m4_defs':
/home/mikehan/fvwm/modules/FvwmM4/FvwmM4.c(.text+0x546): warning:
mktemp() possibly used unsafely; consider using mkstemp()
x_pager.c: In function `UpdateWindowShape':
x_pager.c:821: warning: assignment from incompatible pointer type

For x_pager.c, the fix appears trivial. The alloc'd memory needs to be
cast when assigned to the pointer:

diff -u -r1.90 x_pager.c
--- x_pager.c   2000/04/18 16:12:30     1.90
+++ x_pager.c   2000/04/19 04:51:19
@@ -818,7 +818,7 @@
   shape_count =
     ndesks + ((Scr.CurrentDesk < desk1 || Scr.CurrentDesk >desk2) ? 0 : 1);
 
-  shape = alloca (shape_count * sizeof (XRectangle));
+  shape = (XRectangle *)alloca (shape_count * sizeof (XRectangle));
 
   if (shape == NULL)
     return;

This appears to fix the warning, and I'm blithely assuming it works
the same. As far as the mk[s]temp() complaint, the suggestion to use
mkstemp() sounds good, but I don't know if there's some reason not to
use mkstemp().
