Well, All the stuff in sysconfdir/fvwm are script or form. Form*,
Script*
both use FvwmForm, or FvwmScript. 
Config* could probably be really considered a "Config" file that should
be in etcdir (sysconfdir).

But Script* and Form* technically by standards would not be config
files,
because they are fvwm-native FvwmForm and FvwmScript, and should be in a
shared directory such as FVWM_PREFIX/share/fvwm, instead of
ETCDIR/fvwm..
This would deduct logical good practice to keep them like that.
I'll give you an example: Config files, like system.fvwm2rc, and
fvwm/Config*, belong in ETCDIR/fvwm/, where Script* and Form* belong in
FVWM_PREFIX/share/fvwm. If I keep my sysconfdir as /etc/X11/fvwm, like
Debian, RedHat, or most distros do, then those Scripts and Forms are
eating up my very valuable / partition. I keep my / at 80mb, which is
more than enough for what _should_ be stored in / and /etc. /usr, /var,
and /home are seperate partitions, and /opt, is an optional partition
which some distros, and people, use. I stopped making an /opt, myself,
but once I get a bigger HD, I'll use /opt again.


You see my point? If not, feel free to ask me some questions. I'm all
ears and all answers.



