Hello FVWM workers!

I see that the list is going on strong ...

On Thu, 20 Apr 2000, Mikhael Goikhman wrote:

> On 20 Apr 2000 14:02:36 -0400, Dan Espen wrote:
> > 
> > Mikhael Goikhman <migo@cortext.co.il> writes:

> > > We have in fvwm:
> > >   FVWM_MODULEDIR='${libexecdir}/${PACKAGE}/${VERSION}'
> > >   FVWM_CONFIGDIR='${sysconfdir}/${PACKAGE}'
> > > 
> > > In FVWM_CONFIGDIR currently we install configs (Config*), scripts
> > > (Script*), and forms (Form*), I think none of them belong to $sysconfdir,
> > > i.e. there is nothing that fvwm may want to install to /etc (if distros
> > > use /etc for ${sysconfdir}).

[ ... ]

> I remember well why FVWM_MODULEDIR is this and not another. It is ok.
> However, I don't recall reading about FVWM_CONFIGDIR, so I went to
> archives: http://www.hpc.uh.edu/cgi-bin/w3glimpse/fvwm?query=sysconfdir
> 
> There were no scripts and forms installed in FVWM_CONFIGDIR in 19971208,
> so still this old discussion does not explain why they should go to /etc.

This is true.  At the time, the only way to configure FVWM was through
system.fvwm2rc or $HOME/.fvwm2rc.  When I was doing the autoconfiscation,
I used $sysconfigdir for the system-wide configuration file.

The forms and whatnot came along later.

I think that, to sort this out, one must decide what sort of directory
layout is desirable.  You can choose GNU standards, or the FHS, or
historical layouts from sunos, or some ad-hoc scheme.  Naturally, I'd be
inclined to pick one of the first two, which I believe are compatible, or
mostly so.

The advantage of using the FHS, say, is that you have a document to work
from (http://www.pathname.com/fhs) which already describes where config
files & script files belong.  

Then the hard part: deciding which files qualify as "configuration" files.
To me it is clear that "system.fvwm2rc" qualifies, while theme images, for
example, do not.


> So I am still quite sure that ${datadir} should be used instead of
> ${sysconfdir} for FVWM_CONFIGDIR.

Perhaps there ought to be a third option: separate themes and scripts from
configuration files.


Keep up the good work,
-Steve



