On 21 Apr 2000 15:01:48 -0400, Dan Espen wrote:
> 
> > FVWM_USERDIR now defaults to $HOME/.fvwm not $HOME. FVWM_USERDIR directory
> > is now created if needed. FVWM_USERDIR variable is now exported for all
> > subprocesses, not only for modules (just like FVWM_MODULEDIR).
> 
> So you would only export FVWM_USERDIR to go back to using $HOME or some
> other directory.

If $FVWM_USERDIR is defined, it is used, otherwise it is exported (and
used) to be ~/.fvwm. Exporting is needed to help shell scripts (like
fvwm-*) to know where to put their user config files without guessing.

> > This patch does not contradict with the Olivier's suggestion (corrected
> > by me) to add additional SearchPath to extend FVWM_USERDIR & FVWM_DATADIR.
> 
> What does this mean?
> Are these paths or directories?
> I think they have to be directories.

FVWM_USERDIR and FVWM_DATADIR are directories. Currently they are both
used for searching fvwm files. The new suggestion (not included in
this patch) is to support additional variable $FVWM_SEARCHPATH or a new
fvwm command SearchPath to add additional directories to search for.
So if you define: SearchPath ${HOME}:/usr/local/fvwm, - fvwm and modules
search in: FVWM_USERDIR (i.e. ~/.fvwm), ~, /usr/local/fvwm, FVWM_DATADIR.

Regards,
Mikhael.
