I've spent some time debugging the hang when two FvwmAutos are
started.  It seems to happen when they actually try to raise a
window.  All locking (UNLOCK messages) seems to work ok.  But
then, fvwm hangs in a read() call in events.c (line 2361):

  FD_ZERO(&in_fdset);
  FD_SET(x_fd,&in_fdset);
  /* nothing is done here if fvem was compiled without session support */
  if (sm_fd >= 0)
    FD_SET(sm_fd, &in_fdset);
  FD_ZERO(&out_fdset);
  for(i=0; i<npipes; i++) {
    if(readPipes[i]>=0)
      FD_SET(readPipes[i], &in_fdset);
    if(pipeQueue[i]!= NULL)
      FD_SET(writePipes[i], &out_fdset);
  }

  DBUG("My_XNextEvent","waiting for module input/output");
  XFlush(dpy);
  if (fvwmSelect(fd_width, &in_fdset, &out_fdset, 0, timeoutP) > 0) {

    /* Check for module input. */
    for (i=0; i<npipes; i++) {
      if ((readPipes[i] >= 0) && FD_ISSET(readPipes[i], &in_fdset)) {
-->     if (read(readPipes[i], &targetWindow, sizeof(Window)) > 0) {
          DBUG("My_XNextEvent","calling HandleModuleInput");
          HandleModuleInput(targetWindow, i, NULL);
    } else {
          DBUG("My_XNextEvent","calling KillModule");
          KillModule(i);
        }
      }
      if ((writePipes[i] >= 0) && FD_ISSET(writePipes[i], &out_fdset)) {
        DBUG("My_XNextEvent","calling FlushQueue");
        FlushQueue(i);
      }
    }

So, since the file descriptor has changed, the only explanation I
can think of is that less than sizeof(Window) bytes are available
on the input pipe.  Does this make sense?

Since every packet sent by a module contains a 'window' entry
(sizeof(Window)), there are several explanations:

 1) The module sent trash.
 2) Part of the input has already been read somewhere else.
 3) fvwmSelect lies about the state of the file descriptor.

All of this seems very unlikely to me.  Any better ideas?

Bye

Dominik ^_^

