On Tue, Apr 25, 2000 at 10:38:46AM +1000, Chris Rankin wrote:
> > 
> > I've spent some time debugging the hang when two FvwmAutos are
> > started.  It seems to happen when they actually try to raise a
> > window.  All locking (UNLOCK messages) seems to work ok.  But
> > then, fvwm hangs in a read() call in events.c (line 2361):
> 
> > -->     if (read(readPipes[i], &targetWindow, sizeof(Window)) > 0) {
> 
> Is it possible that the same descriptor is appearing twice in the
> readPipes[] array? This would mean that the first read would empty the
> pipe and the second would then block.

No, that's not what happens (I checked it with a few fprintf's).
The two instances of FvwmAuto have the module numbers 6 and 7 in
my setup and the read pipe numbers 18 and 20.  The last thing I
see before fvwm blocks is that the select call returns with both
pipes (18 and 20) changed.  The read() call on pipe 18 returns
successfully, but the read() call on pipe 20 blocks for no
apparent reason.

---------- one hour later ----------

Okay, this is what happens:

0) Both FvwmAutos (I'll call them FA1 and FA2 from now)
   deciade at the same time that the focused window must be
   raised.  Both put a 'silent raise' into their pipe.
1) Fvwm enters the module input loop in events.c.
2) Fvwm reads 'silent raise' from FA1's pipe.
3) Fvwm raises the window and puts a M_RAISE_WINDOW packet
   into FA1's pipe.  This type of packet is in FvwmAuto's
   sync mask, thus fvwm waits for an 'UNLOCK' response from
   FA1.
4) FA1 responds with 'UNLOCK'.
5) Fvwm sends the M_RAISE_WINDOW to FA2 and waits for 'UNLOCK'.
6) Fvwm is now in the loop in module_interface.c, lines 1205
   to 1272.
7) FA2 puts 'UNLOCK' into the pipe.
8) Fvwm reads 'silent raise' from FA2's pipe before it can get
   the 'UNLOCK':
     while (HandleModuleInput(targetWindow, module, NULL) != 66);
9) Again, fvwm sends M_RAISE_WINDOW packet to FA1 and gets
   'UNLOCK'.
10) Fvwm sends M_RAISE_WINDOW packet to FA2 and gets the old
    'UNLOCK' that was already queued.  FA2 puts another
    'UNLOCK' into the pipe.
11) Fvwm returns from the HandleModuleInput() call in step 8.
12) In the next pass of the loop, Fvwm reads the expected
    'UNLOCK' from FA2's queue.
13) Fvwm breaks the loop and returns to the loop in events.c.
14) Fvwm tries to read from FA2's queue which is empty now.

==> BANG

When the select call returned that FA2's filedescriptor changed
in the first place, this was because of the 'Silent Raise'. But
this string was eaten up while FA1's input was processed (step 8).
So when fvwm finally got around to read from FA2's pipe, nothing
was left to be read.

One simple but inefficient fix comes to my mind: select()
the module input pipes one by one, not in one big loop.

Another idea:  why do the read pipes block?  The code
in events.c:

  if (read(readPipes[i], &targetWindow, sizeof(Window)) > 0) {
    DBUG("My_XNextEvent","calling HandleModuleInput");
    HandleModuleInput(targetWindow, i, NULL);
  } else {
    DBUG("My_XNextEvent","calling KillModule");
    KillModule(i);
  }

could be rewritten like this:

  if (read(readPipes[i], &targetWindow, sizeof(Window)) > 0) {
    DBUG("My_XNextEvent","calling HandleModuleInput");
    HandleModuleInput(targetWindow, i, NULL);
  } else if (/*error condition*/) {
    DBUG("My_XNextEvent","calling KillModule");
    KillModule(i);
  } else {
    /* nothing read, ignore */
  }

There are several places in module_interface.c that would have
to be changed too.

Chris, can you do something about it?

Bye

Dominik ^_^

