%% Mikhael Goikhman <migo@cortext.co.il> writes:

  mg> On 26 Apr 2000 15:08:27 -0400, Paul D. Smith wrote:

  >> Can a module find out what other modules are running?  I know I should
  >> just go look :-/.  It seems like it would be a useful thing to provide
  >> modules the ability to ask for a list of information about registered
  >> modules.  If so, when FvwmAuto first starts it could ask for this list,
  >> check if there's a different FvwmAuto, and die if so.

  mg> Ability to check for module uniqueness is good, but should be optional.
  mg> Say, using UniqueModule command.

No, I meant it would be up to the module to determine what to do.  In
other words, fvwm would merely supply the module list, then the module
would decide what to do with it.

FvwmAuto would check for any other module besides itself (the module
list would need to contain uniquifying info, like maybe the pipe FD
numbers) and die if any such existed.

Other modules might do other things (maybe you could write a "module
manager module" :).

  mg> All current "event" modules (FvwmAuto, FvwmBanner, FvwmEvent) are
  mg> very generic/configurable, i.e. they can be programmed to execute
  mg> any arbitrary fvwm function, not only autoraise windows, or set
  mg> background images, or play sounds, or all together.

FvwmAuto doesn't fit with the rest of the items you list there.  It's
not at all configurable.  I can't see _any_ reason to _ever_ run more
than one.

Unless I'm missing something ...

If there really are reasons to have multiple modules, like for
FvwmEvent, then obviously they wouldn't even bother to check this.

