See my other mail for a detailed analysis of the problem.

>   dv> One simple but inefficient fix comes to my mind: select()
>   dv> the module input pipes one by one, not in one big loop.
> 
> I don't see how this would work: you'd have to have a loop where you
> select with no waiting on each read FD at a time, then loop back to the
> beginning and start over.  But that's a hard loop and will cause FVWM to
> eat all the CPU!  Or, you'd have to give each select a short timeout,
> but then the responsiveness of your modules goes incrementally down as
> you add more modules, even relatively inactive ones, since each one gets
> a little timeslice (and of course, your CPU usage for FVWM still goes
> up).  Or, you'd select with no wait, then sleep a little, then start
> over, but now you're slowing down all modules (and CPU usage is still
> higher).
> 
> I think this should be avoided if possible.

Of course you're right, Paul.  The loop would eat up all CPU.  I didn't
mean this 'fix' seriously anyway.

>   dv> Another idea:  why do the read pipes block?
> 
> Well, the harder part is setting the FD for non-blocking reads in the
> first place.  Unfortunately the method for doing that isn't as portable
> as you might hope, IIRC... I think some older systems can't even do it.
> You'd probably need some autoconf support for this.  I played with this
> a good bit a couple of years ago in GNU make, I'll see if I can remember
> the details.

Then, what can we do?  Is it possible to code this approach:

 1) select() for all pipes
 2) handle input from the first changed pipe
 3) remove the changed pipe and all unchanged ones from the set
 4) select() again on the remaining pipes, return immediately if
    no input is available.
 5) repeat 2-5 until no pipes have input

I'm not sure how select() works exactly.

