This can happen with other (different) modules too.  Fvwm will
freeze if the following conditions are met:

 1) Two modules send a command at the same time (the commands can
    be different).  The important part is that the select() call
    will report that both module pipes have changed.

     AND

 2) The command from the first module triggers a message from fvwm
    to the second module that is selected by the module's
    SyncMask.

The following modules currently use the SyncMask:

  FvwmAnimate  M_(DE)ICONIFY, M_STRING
  FvwmAuto     M_FOCUS_CHANGE, M_RAISE_WINDOW, M_LOWER_WINDOW
  FvwmGtk      M_STRING
  FvwmIconBox  M_(DE)ICONIFY
  FvwmIconMan  M_(DE)ICONIFY
  FvwmTaskBar  M_(DE)ICONIFY
  FvwmWinList  M_(DE)ICONIFY

As far as I know, only FvwmAuto sends anything to fvwm not
directly caused by user interaction.  Condition (2) can
be fulfilled easily, e.g. by iconifying a window.  The
difficult part is to have input from another module at the
same time.  FvwmConsole may be a good candidate to force
this situation:

 - Paste many lines like 'next iconify toggle' into the
   FvwmConsole window.
 - At the same time repeatedly click on a button in FvwmIconMan
   fast.

Hold on, I'll give it a try...

--------- 5 minutes later ---------

Yup, I get the same problem.  What I did is this:

 - KillModule *
   (to make sure the modules are in the correct order)
 - Open an xemacs window and write
     'next (emacs*) iconify toggle'
   1000 times
 - Start FvwmConsole from a menu (it's important that
   FvwmConsole is started first - order matters).
 - Start FvwmIconMan from a menu.
 - Paste the complete xemacs buffer 10 times into the
   console window.
 - While fvwm is busy (de)iconifying, hit any button in
   FvwmIconMan often.  Once in a while stop doing this
   and watch what happens.

==> Sometimes fvwm stops (de)iconifying.  In this
    situation it is frozen until I press a button in the
    IconMan window to feed the read() call.

The problem with FvwmAuto is that there is nothing the user
can do to wake up the idle module because FvwmAuto doesn't
take user input, only input from fvwm - and fvwm is already
frozen.

BTW, a possible 'solution' could be some kind of heartbeat
from the modules.  FvwmAuto could send a 'Nop' every 5
seconds or so to keep fvwm alive :-)

Bye

