> This can happen with other (different) modules too.  Fvwm will
> freeze if the following conditions are met:
> 
>  1) Two modules send a command at the same time (the commands can
>     be different).  The important part is that the select() call
>     will report that both module pipes have changed.
> 
>      AND
> 
>  2) The command from the first module triggers a message from fvwm
>     to the second module that is selected by the module's
>     SyncMask.

OK, I've poked around the code a little and digested Dominik's bug
synopsis. In summary: it looks like the root of the problem is the way
that BroadcastPacket(M_RAISE_WINDOW) calls PositiveWrite() for all
modules. PositiveWrite() expects a reply from each descriptor and
therefore destroys the "read-state" of every descriptor as recorded
earlier in My_XNextEvent().

I'll throw out a few clay pigeons for everyone to shoot at:
- we can either try to preserve My_XNextEvent()'s idea of which
  descriptors are still readable, or we can recognise that certain
  functions will trash this information.

- if we can spot when My_XNextEvent()'s readable descriptor set
  (in_fdset) has been invalidated then we could do something like:

  reset:
  if (fvwmSelect(fd_width, &in_fdset, &out_fdset, 0, timeoutP) > 0) {
    ...
      HandleModuleInput(targetWindow, i, NULL);
      if (descriptorsChanged) goto reset;

  This approach is hopefully low-impact, which is good since we're
  aiming for 2.4.

- Having thought about what I've just written, I am now worried that
  this goto approach might make fvwm neglect pipes in readPipes[i]
  with large "i" in favour of pipes with smaller "i". (Did that make
  sense?) Maybe instead we could just call fvwmSelect() again using
  the existing fd_sets and a timeout of zero? This way, we would only
  check that pipes that we thought had data still do have data. We
  would also have to call FD_CLR() for each descriptor:

  if (fvwmSelect(fd_width, &in_fdset, &out_fdset, 0, timeoutP) > 0) {

    /* Check for module input. */
    for (i=0; i<npipes; i++) {
      if ((readPipes[i] >= 0) && FD_ISSET(readPipes[i], &in_fdset)) {
        FD_CLR(readPipes[i], &in_fdset);

        if (read(readPipes[i], &targetWindow, sizeof(Window)) > 0) {
          DBUG("My_XNextEvent","calling HandleModuleInput");
          HandleModuleInput(targetWindow, i, NULL);

          /* reset our idea of which descriptors have data waiting to
             be read, as necessary ...
             Maybe use return code from HandleModuleInput instead of
             this global "descriptors have changed" variable? */
          if (descriptorsChanged &&
              fvwmSelect(fd_width, &in_fdset, &out_fdset, 0, 0) <= 0) {
            break;
          }

	} else {
          DBUG("My_XNextEvent","calling KillModule");
          KillModule(i);
        }
      }
      if ((writePipes[i] >= 0) && FD_ISSET(writePipes[i], &out_fdset)) {
        FD_CLR(writePipes[i], &out_fdset);

        DBUG("My_XNextEvent","calling FlushQueue");
        FlushQueue(i);
      }
    } /* for */

- is there any way for a pipe to receive "exceptional" data? If we
  could get the UNLOCK to be notified via select()'s fdset *exceptfds
  argument then the read-state would remain intact. (I have very
  little hope here - the man pages imply that this is more of a
  socket-protocol thing.)

- I was going to look for a solution whereby in_fdset (and out_fdset?)
  aren't invalidated in the first place, but that turns very evil very
  quickly by striking at the root of BroadcastPacket and the SyncMask
  functionality ...

What do people think? How many functions would need to be modified to
support the "descriptors have changed" functionality? Or do you think
I'm barking up totally the wrong tree?

Cheers,
Chris.
