> 

I think you've hit the nail on the head.  Something from my dim and
distant networking days is coming back.  It's "out of band" signaling.

Fvwm wants an UNLOCK from every SyncMask message and the current problem
is that it can't get at them until it has processed all the other
messages the module has sent.

The correct solution to this class of problems is for fvwm to wait for
the UNLOCK command without doing anything else and then process any
other module commands in normal order.

We have a choice of ways to do this:

1) don't use the module pipes to pass the UNLOCK message, we could use
an extra pipe (not backwards compatible, extra file descriptors), or
maybe we could use signals.

2) use the module pipes and buffer any commands received until the
UNLOCK, this is similar to the way XLib works, you can look for a
certain event type, other events received are added to the queue and
will be retrieved by the next XNextEvent().

If the signals way is portable and safe I think I'd prefer that, the
sync code could be something like:

	SendMessage();
	SetSig(USR2, interrupt);
	sleep(some_large_timeout);
	SetSig(USR2, ignore);

You could even replace the sleep with a (set cursor to busy, wait for a
timeout or escape key sequence or signal).

Cheers,
Tim.
