> >
> >
> >Unfortunatelly this does not work as expected now, I suppose, because of
> >syncronization/pipe problems. Try running two FvwmAuto's first.
> 
> Based on Dominik's description, this should work, shouldn't it? The
> synchronous behavior of multiple FvwmAutos shouldn't be relevant if
> all your FvwmAutos are running with different delay timings. Did I
> misunderstand?
> 
> What exactly is the purpose of having synchronous module behavior here
> for focus/raise/lower?

It's necessary to synchronize FvwmAuto and fvwm to avoid race
conditions.  In the past we didn't use the SyncMask for FvwmAuto,
but when the user had Mouse/SloppyFocus, dragging the pointer
across several windows could lead to a random window being raised.
Setting the SyncMask dramatically reduces this risk.

> I'm sort of interested in pursuing the idea of
> integrating FvwmAuto into FvwmEvent -- this would require adding delay
> timers to FvwmEvent, and ideally should also include the ability to
> define multiple actions per event on different timers. But generally
> speaking, FvwmEvent provides a pretty nice generic framework for doing
> what FvwmAuto does. It can certainly handle the simplest case
> scenario of autoraise with zero delay.

Well, perhaps we should think about integrating FvwmEvent into
the main module (along with FvwmAuto).  With the current module
interface, asynchronous event handling is a pain and often causes
hard to debug race conditions.  Just a thought.

Bye

Dominik ^_^

