>Previously from Bob Woodside:
>[snip]
>2) Replace the CONFIGARGSNEW macro technique of invoking
>make_new_vpacket with a bit of code (or wrap the call with a bit of
>intermediate code) that would convert all the int items to longs before
>calling make_new_vpacket. This may be the best way to go.
>
>[snip]
>
>4) Do a major investigation of all the modules that use
>M_CONFIGURE_WINDOW to see how much trouble it would be to fix them to
>use the packet as it would be sent with the correction above to use the
>actual lengths of the int fields. The problem I see with this approach
>is that it would definitely break the old binary compatibility that
>several people spent a lot of time and effort to try to maintain (i.e.,
>the idea was that everything in the packet *before* the new window_flags
>struct was supposed to continue to look just the way it always did).

Well, grepping for CONFIGURE I find that about half the modules that
care about M_CONFIGURE_WINDOW packets are already using vpacket.h.
Exceptions I see: FvwmIconMan, FvwmIdent, FvwmDebug, FvwmSave,
FvwmSaveDesk. I don't see that it should be too difficult to convert
these to use the ConfigWinPacket struct in libs/vpacket.h. Of course,
there are still non-core modules like FvwmKb (it doesn't care about
CONFIGURE and ADD) and TkGoodStuff.

Personally, I think converting the core modules to refer to vpacket.h
is a good thing no matter what, so I've done an ugly hack in
FvwmIconMan/fvwm.c to make it use vpacket.h and ConfigWinPacket.
Fortunately, Brady had written it so that he'd already setup IconMan
to treat the body as a struct, so conversion was easy. Unfortuantely,
it looks messy because ConfigWinPacket doesn't really "fit in" with
the rest of the code... Still, I compiled it -Wall without trouble and
it seems to work fine. See attachment for the diff -u. If there's
interest, I can go through the other modules and convert them too.
